    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_23489557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/23489557" />
    <a title="Roy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/723173-roy"><img alt="Roy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1199472759p2/723173.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/23489557?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roy" href="/user/show/723173-roy">Roy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Umberto Eco fans</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer23489557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17442594740903333555">There were three reasons why I read this book. One, Eco, I&apos;d heard so much talk about his work (fiction and non-). Two, the setting, the Middle Ages, a historical period that is a bit of a gap for me. Three, an unreliable narrator, Usual Suspects is one of my favorite movies for this reason. Fictional stories are all lies, but in that world, you expect truth, but when you find out the fiction you are experiencing is also a fiction, well that is just delicious. <br/><br/>I enjoyed Baudolino&apos;s world where l</span>
  <span id="freeText17442594740903333555" style="display:none">There were three reasons why I read this book. One, Eco, I'd heard so much talk about his work (fiction and non-). Two, the setting, the Middle Ages, a historical period that is a bit of a gap for me. Three, an unreliable narrator, Usual Suspects is one of my favorite movies for this reason. Fictional stories are all lies, but in that world, you expect truth, but when you find out the fiction you are experiencing is also a fiction, well that is just delicious. <br /><br />I enjoyed Baudolino's world where lies become truth. More fascinating, faith, even when focused on a lie, can manifest things into reality. If people believe it, it becomes so. Eco is a theorists, and so it is no surprise that his books would have a strong intellectual backbone. He also plays a nimble game with the narration as it flips from a story in the past being told by a character to a narrator telling a story in the present. I've seen other authors struggle with this in other books and I appreciated Eco's ability to keep this told tale fresh and in the moment.<br /><br />Where I lost enthusiasm for this book was the meandering biographical back story in the beginning. There are a lot of events in the first half that end up being not being very relevant. Once you hit the crusades, where the plot picks up, and then the fantastical parts in the end, then the story goes somewhere. We meet Baudolino almost in the womb, and I wish we could have started when he was a man. <br /><br />I found the ending satisfying, although it leaves room for what would be a very maddening sequel (I doubt Eco is penning Baudolino 2). I still intend to read some of Eco's better loved books, so he has not lost me as a reader, but I also can't recommend this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17442594740903333555" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

